New Chromebook Deployment Sessions Have Been Scheduled For Next Week!

If you have an incoming 6th grade student or incoming 9th grade student, please sign up for one of our contactless, drive-thru deployments! It takes less than five minutes and you will leave with a new Chromebook for your child for the upcoming school year!

It is important for us to get all of our 8th grade Chromebooks back so they can be cleaned, disinfected and prepared for re-deployment to the elementary schools for the upcoming school year, so please help us out!

You can get more information and sign up for a time slot at this link:

https://sites.google.com/norwood.k12.ma.us/mustang-technology/2020-grade-6-and-9-new-chromebook-deployment

post_text:
The Norwood Public Schools Elementary curriculum coordinators have developed a Summer Learning program that includes activities in math and literacy to ensure students continue to grow and learn throughout this summer. There is a mix of online and paper based activities available on the student menus.

Classroom teachers will be sharing all of the program details with students in grades 1-5 next week during Google Meets. Paper-based materials will be available at each elementary school during the grab and go lunch distribution next Monday Wednesday and Friday. A digital format of all resources will also be available. Stay tuned for more details as we wrap up the school year and get ready for SUMMER!

For our parents, we have compiled the following list of resources that you may find useful when talking about race with your children. Please know that this is not a complete list and creating this list is only the beginning of how we will support the Norwood Community through this challenging time. As we continue to learn and grow as an educational community, we will add to this list of resources for our families and the community at large. The Norwood Public School District remains committed to working together, as a community, to foster inclusivity and celebrate our cultural, linguistic and racial diversity.

post_text:
Congratulations to NPS ELA Department Chair, Teresa Drummey, who was named Norwood Teacher of the Year by the Orient Masonic Lodge. Ms. Drummey was nominated by the students of her AP English class and is well known to spark a love of literature in those who attend her class. She has taught countless numbers of NHS students literature classics, and many students are known to use their notes from her class on Dante's Inferno when they go on to study it in college!

Congratulations to all of our Teacher of the Year nominees, including the four other chosen finalists:

Jason Andrews - Coakley Middle School
Janet Lynch - Cleveland Elementary
Karen Gorman - St. Catherine of Siena School
Christine LaRaia - Norwood High School

The Town of Norwood in partnership with Norwood Food Service will be providing FREE Grab & Go dinner meals at selected sites. These meals will be provided to all requesting Norwood families and will be available for pick up from any of the community elementary schools on Wednesdays. post_text: NPS Food Services Director, Eli Norris, and the food services department unveiled two new programs this week, Mood Boost and Discovery Kitchen! The Norwood Public Schools and Chartwells K12 wants every student to leave the cafeteria happier and healthier than they came. The Mood Boost and Discovery Kitchen programs make learning about and tasting healthy foods delicious and fun! This week, Chef Norris and his staff demonstrated the Discovery Kitchen for some students at the Little Mustang Preschool Academy by making some healthy chicken stir fry and vegetables! He also demonstrated the Mood Boost program for our district administration team with a tasting of delicious avocado and strawberry smoothies. Be in the lookout for both programs coming to a school in your neighborhood!

post_text:
Come to the Day House on November 2 or 3 to see over fifty pieces of artwork from Norwood High School students. For the exhibition all of NHS' photography and upper-level art students create work influenced by the life and photography of F. Holland Day, a pioneer of American Fine Art Photography. The art display is free and open to the public on Nov 2 and 3 from 1-3pm. The Day House is located at 93 Day St.

To create the artwork for this exhibition, students toured the Day House to learn about its historical background as well as the significance of F. Holland Day, a pioneer of American fine art photography. The tour was given by members of the Norwood Historical Society. After the tour, the students were free to explore the house as well as sketch their ideas or take photographs. Through this assignment and exhibition, students connected with the artistic heritage of Norwood as well as contributing to the cultural life of Norwood. This exhibition is a unique opportunity to see advanced studio art and photography students’ work in an important historical setting.

post_text: Lots of representation from the Norwood Public Schools today at the state-wide MassCUE technology conference at Gillette Stadium. Balch teachers Molly Cotter and Darlene Follett along with elementary math coordinator, Jill Milton, presented on blended and personalized learning. NPS library/media teachers Aaron Reuland and Donna Miller presented on makerspace activities. We also had students from Norwood High School presenting about the NHS Global Citizenship Program! Amazing job by amazing students and educators!

As you may be aware, Norwood Public Schools has been exploring the important topic of school start times and the impact on our students’ health, development, and academics. The School Start Times Task Force is in the process of distributing surveys throughout NPS to help us analyze information specific to Norwood.

We appreciate your participation and want your voice to be heard in this process. We are asking all parents/ guardians of students grades preschool through 12th grade to take a brief, anonymous online parent/ guardian survey. If you have more than one child in our schools, please plan on taking the survey for each child. You can take the survey by clicking the following link:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdcVQoj5WYZyhBTmPfqiulmjr-nOsKvjEb0efMCdnRk9WJAjg/viewform

Please complete this survey by October 14.

NHS Engineering and Robotics Teacher, Dr. Mike Crowley, held another successful technology olympics this spring. Each year students in his classes build rover vehicles and complete a one mile course from the high school to the Cleveland Elementary School and back with the goal of using the least amount of power possible. This year Chris Bellande, James Gamel and Stephen Petithomme set an NHS Technology Olympics record by using a mere 18 milliwatts of power to complete the course! Click on the link to see their finish.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/10G_HtIKRz0AjZzPI5QjSv5lYXZhgjZzt/view?usp=sharing

post_text: Today was the 2nd annual “NHS Senior Walk” in which graduating seniors dress in their caps and gowns and walk through the elementary schools they attended in Norwood while the current elementary students in those schools cheer them on! Students at the schools made signs and cards for the graduates. Graduating seniors also got to visit their former teachers and even have some recess time with current students! Congratulations to the entire class of 2019!

shared_text:
Wade Institute for Science Education
December 14, 2018 at 5:42 PM ·

This has been a busy week! On Wednesday, we made solar ovens and silly putty with high school #educators from Norwood Public Schools. Today, we investigated physical science and chemistry topics with #teachers from Walpole Public Schools. Both of these hands-on, minds-on #professionaldevelopment sessions were designed by our Education Specialists as part of our Customized Professional Learning Services.

Find out how we work with schools and school districts through our Customized Professional Learning Services by visiting: http://mits.org/customized-school-services.
